This seemed like SUCH a great idea:

https://developer.mapquest.com/documentation/api/static-map/

Software could use it to generate a .jpg file of the route
the driver had actually taken and that could be included
in the e-mail to the coordinator instead of a link to the
mapquest website.

It would be awesome, except the only way of sending the
actual route would require sending a long list of GPS
coordinates - and I don't care how well you compress it,
you're not going to get it small enough where an even
slightly interesting route can be sent with http GET.

Mapquest appears not to support static mapping with POST
(as confirmed by Mapquest support).

Ended up sending coordinator link to a web page which
can post the information to the live mapper.

Why is that so bad?

Firstly, this means that the coordinator must be on the
Internet to view the map ... which they probably are if
they are reading e-mail.

But more importantly, the live map could be entirely
different than when the driver drove the route.  Roads
come, roads go.
